The '''Arundel Society''' was founded at [[London]] in 1849 and named after the [[Thomas Howard, 21st Earl of Arundel|Earl of Arundel]], the famous collector of the [[Arundel marbles|Arundel Marbles]] and one of the first great [[English people|English]] patrons and lovers of the arts. The society was originally the idea of the lawyer [[Charles Henry Bellenden Ker|Bellenden Ker]] and was founded at a meeting in the house of the famous painter [[Charles Lock Eastlake|Charles Eastlake]], attended by Eastlake, Ker, Giovanni Aubrey Bezzi, and Edmund Oldfield. The society's purpose was to promote knowledge of the art works of the old Italian, Flemish, and other European masters.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Nineteenth Century|title=The Arundel Society|author=[[William Henry Gregory|Gregory. W. H.]]|date=April 1884|pages=610–625|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dL8CAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA610}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=On the Vernon Dante|author=Barlow, Henry Clark|year=1870|location=London|publisher=Williams and Norgate|chapter=Aubrey Bezzi was a music master in Plymouth and became Eastlake's assistant secretary in the Royal Commission of Fine Arts|pages=36–37|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sSooYblX3xEC&pg=PA36}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Complete Works of John Ruskin|editor=Cook, E. T. |editor2=Wedderburn, Alexander |year=1908|quote=Edmund Oldfield (1817-1902), M.A., F.S.A. ... assistant keeper of antiquities at the British Museum; and at one time private secretary to Layard at the Office of Works.|volume=Library Edition, Vol. XXXV; Praeterita and Dilecta|location=London|publisher=George Allen|page=384|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2GxAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA384}}</ref> Much of the work of the society consisted of publishing chromolithographs of Italian art works, especially fresco paintings, of earlier centuries and raising public awareness for the preservation of these works.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Blackwood's Edinburgh Magazine|date=Oct 1860|title=The fresco-paintings of Italy—the Arundel Society|volume=LXXXVIII|issue=DXL|pages=458–471|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kLMCAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA458}}</ref> One of the people most responsible for furthering the goals of the society was [[Austen Henry Layard|Henry Layard]], who joined in 1852. Some of the other important early members were [[John Ruskin]], [[Charles Thomas Newton]], and [[Henry Liddell]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Complete Works of John Ruskin|editor=Cook, E. T. |editor2=Wedderburn, Alexander |year=1903|volume=Library Edition, Vol. IV; Modern Painters, Vol. II|location=London|publisher=George Allen|page=xliv}}</ref> Members of the Society's Council in 1877 included [[Frederick William Burton]], [[Francis Charteris, 10th Earl of Wemyss|Lord Elcho (Francis Charteris)]], [[Edward Poynter]], [[George Edmund Street]], [[Philip Charles Hardwick]], [[George Richmond (painter)|George Richmond]], and the architect [[John Norton (architect)|John Norton]].<ref>{{cite book|title=A List of Members of the Society, Corrected to September, 1877|year=1877|location=London|publisher=Arundel Society for Promoting the Knowledge of Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wmBIAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> The society was discontinued in 1897.
==Arundel Club== The '''Arundel Club''' was a society founded in London in 1904 for the purpose of continuing more effectively the work of the Arundel Society, which had encouraged the study of art by reproducing the best works of the old masters. The Arundel Club went further by copying and publishing important works in private collections previously inaccessible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jMaCnQAACAAJ&dq=Arundel+Club&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiF4s6fxv_TAhVIOyYKHd_3ACYQ6AEIJzAA|title=The Arundel Club: For the Publication of Reproductions of Works of Art in Private Collections and Elsewhere|first=Arundel|last=Club|date=20 May 2017|publisher=J.J. Waddington|accessdate=20 May 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref>
